    "body" : "<h2>Wrong formatting pattern</h2>\n<p>As others noted, date-time formatting patterns are <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Case_sensitivity\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">case-sensitive</a>. Read the Javadoc while programming to learn such important facts.</p>\n<h2>Wrong class</h2>\n<p>The <code>java.util.Date</code> class does not represent a date. (The misnomer is one of many flaws in this legacy class.) That class represents a moment, a point on the timeline as seen in UTC. Yet its <code>toString</code> method confusingly applies the JVM’s current default time zone. (Yet another flaw in this legacy class.)</p>\n<h2>Right class</h2>\n<p>For your date-time handling work, use only <em>java.time</em> classes.</p>\n<p>For a date-only value, use <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/25/docs/api/java.base/java/time/LocalDate.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>java.time.LocalDate</code></a>.</p>\n<p>To determine today, pass your desired/expected time zone.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>ZoneId z = ZoneId.of( &quot;Africa/Tunis&quot; ) ;\nLocalDate today = LocalDate.now( z ) ;\n</code></pre>\n<h3><em>ISO 8601</em></h3>\n<p>You want text in format of YYYY-MM-DD. That format happens to comply with the standard for date-time text formats, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">ISO 8601</a>. And <em>java.time</em> happens to use that standard by default. So no need to specify any formatting pattern.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>String output = today.toString() ;  // Same as specifying pattern `uuuu-MM-dd`. \n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
